    <h2 class="font-headline text-2xl md:text-3xl font-bold text-on-surface mt-10 mb-4">
      Frequently Asked Questions About Warehouse Packaging Supplies
    </h2>

    <h3 class="font-headline text-xl font-bold text-on-surface mt-6 mb-3">
      What are the essential supplies needed in a warehouse?
    </h3>
    <p class="font-body text-lg text-secondary leading-relaxed mb-4">
      Essential supplies include corrugated carton boxes in multiple sizes, stretch film for palletizing, strapping tape and packing tape, bubble wrap or honeycomb panels for protection, labels, and void fill materials. Most warehouses maintain 3-4 standard box sizes to cover 80% of operations while minimizing inventory complexity.
    </p>

    <h3 class="font-headline text-xl font-bold text-on-surface mt-6 mb-3">
      How do I choose the right box size for my warehouse?
    </h3>
    <p class="font-body text-lg text-secondary leading-relaxed mb-4">
      Select box sizes based on your typical product dimensions, aiming to minimize empty space while maintaining adequate protection. Standard sizes like 5x5x5, 10x10x10, 12x12x12, and 16x12x12 inches cover most applications. Track which sizes you use most frequently and prioritize maintaining those in stock to maximize efficiency.
    </p>

    <h3 class="font-headline text-xl font-bold text-on-surface mt-6 mb-3">
      What is the best stretch film thickness for warehouse use?
    </h3>
    <p class="font-body text-lg text-secondary leading-relaxed mb-4">
      Most warehouses use 20-30 gauge stretch film, which provides good puncture resistance and cost efficiency. Hand-wrapped pallets may need thicker film (25-30+ gauge) due to uneven tension, while machine-wrapped operations can use thinner, more economical film. Consider your load types and handling procedures when selecting thickness.
    </p>

    <h3 class="font-headline text-xl font-bold text-on-surface mt-6 mb-3">
      How much inventory of packaging supplies should a warehouse maintain?
    </h3>
    <p class="font-body text-lg text-secondary leading-relaxed mb-4">
      Maintain 2-4 weeks of supplies based on typical weekly consumption rates. This provides buffer stock for demand variations without excessive storage burden. Calculate your weekly usage of each material, multiply by 3-4, and order accordingly. Many Malaysian warehouses find monthly orders of RM 1,000+ from suppliers provide optimal cost and supply reliability.
    </p>

    <h3 class="font-headline text-xl font-bold text-on-surface mt-6 mb-3">
      Can I return used packaging materials for recycling?
    </h3>
    <p class="font-body text-lg text-secondary leading-relaxed mb-4">
      Yes, corrugated boxes are highly recyclable and can be sold to recyclers, potentially offsetting packaging costs. Stretch film and bubble wrap can be recycled through specialized programs in major Malaysian cities. Many suppliers provide guidance on responsible disposal and can connect you with local recycling partners.
    </p>
